<tool name="create_code_evaluator">
  <description>Propose a new code evaluator for the dataset currently in view. This tool is advertised only when the dataset evaluators tab is mounted. Calling it does NOT itself persist anything — the call renders an inline diff preview in chat that the user reviews. Use it when the user, while viewing a dataset evaluators tab, asks you to author a new code evaluator they can review and commit.</description>
  <when_to_use>
    - The user is viewing the dataset evaluators tab and asks to create, write, or scaffold a new code evaluator for that dataset.
    - The user describes a metric or scoring rule they want as a reusable evaluator for the dataset they are looking at.
  </when_to_use>
  <proposal_flow>
    The create flow has two chat-side stages. Stage 1 is plain chat text from you; stage 2 is the only tool call.
    1. Explain in chat what evaluator you intend to author and why it fits the user's request. Briefly describe the scoring rule, the evaluator language choice, and any sandbox or input-mapping assumptions.
    2. Call `create_code_evaluator` exactly once with the full proposal. This renders an inline diff preview with Confirm / Reject buttons. On Confirm, a prefilled slideover opens and the user clicks Save to persist the evaluator and bind it to this dataset. The tool's output resolves at Save time (accepted), Reject (rejected), or slideover Cancel (rejected). Never call any GraphQL mutation directly.
  </proposal_flow>
  <evaluate_contract>
    - The authored `source_code` MUST define a function literally named `evaluate`. The runtime calls it by name; renaming it will break execution.
    - Only declare parameters drawn from `{output, reference, input, metadata}`. Any other parameter name will fail at execution.
    - Python — positional parameters:
      `def evaluate(output, reference, input, metadata):`
      Any subset is valid, e.g. `def evaluate(output):` or `def evaluate(output, reference):`.
    - TypeScript — a single destructured object:
      `function evaluate({ output, reference, input, metadata }) { ... }`
      Any subset of the destructured keys is valid, e.g. `function evaluate({ output })`.
    - Return either a `{label, score, explanation}` subset (any one, two, or three of those keys) or a bare scalar (string label, numeric score, or boolean). Both shapes are valid in both languages.
    - For dataset-backed experiment evaluators, `output` is the experiment run output and `reference` is the dataset example output. Use sampled dataset context only to infer shape; do not hard-code sample values.
  </evaluate_contract>
  <name>
    - `name` must match `^[a-z0-9]([_a-z0-9-]*[a-z0-9])?$` — lowercase letters, digits, hyphens, or underscores; cannot start or end with a hyphen or underscore.
    - Prefer concise, action-oriented names (e.g. `hallucination-check`, `json-validity`).
  </name>
  <input_mapping>
    - Always send `input_mapping` as a non-null object. The safe default is `{"literalMapping": {}, "pathMapping": {}}`.
    - `pathMapping` keys are evaluator parameter names; values are field-path expressions resolved against upstream data.
    - `literalMapping` keys are evaluator parameter names; values are literal scalars passed straight through.
    - Prefer the safe default mapping for new dataset-backed evaluators. Do not create custom nested path mappings just to reach fields from the sampled examples; declare `input`, `output`, `reference`, or `metadata` and parse nested dicts, lists, or stringified JSON inside `evaluate` instead.
  </input_mapping>
  <sandbox_config>
    - `sandbox_config_id` is REQUIRED. A code evaluator without a sandbox cannot run at experiment time and will be rejected at create time.
    - Pick a config from `<available_sandbox_configs>` below whose `language` matches the evaluator `language`. Do NOT invent or reuse an unrelated ID, and do NOT issue a `sandboxProviders` GraphQL query — the inventory below is authoritative for this turn.
    - If `<available_sandbox_configs>` contains no compatible entry for the requested language, stop the create and tell the user to set one up at `/settings/sandboxes`.
{% if available_sandbox_configs %}
    <available_sandbox_configs>
{% for cfg in available_sandbox_configs %}
      <config id="{{ cfg.sandbox_config_id | sanitize(enclosing_tag="available_sandbox_configs", max_chars=128) | e }}" name="{{ cfg.name | sanitize(enclosing_tag="available_sandbox_configs", max_chars=128) | e }}" language="{{ cfg.language | e }}">
        <internet_access setting="{{ cfg.internet_access | e }}" backend_capability="{{ cfg.internet_access_mode | e }}"/>
        <dependencies supported="{{ 'true' if cfg.supports_dependencies else 'false' }}">
{% for pkg in cfg.dependencies %}
          <package>{{ pkg | sanitize(enclosing_tag="package", max_chars=256) | e }}</package>
{% endfor %}
        </dependencies>
        <env_vars supported="{{ 'true' if cfg.supports_env_vars else 'false' }}">
{% for name in cfg.env_var_names %}
          <name>{{ name | sanitize(enclosing_tag="name", max_chars=128) | e }}</name>
{% endfor %}
        </env_vars>
      </config>
{% endfor %}
    </available_sandbox_configs>
{% else %}
    <available_sandbox_configs/>
{% endif %}
  </sandbox_config>
  <output_configs>
    - `output_configs` is an array. ALWAYS propose at least one entry — you authored the `evaluate()` body, so you know what it returns and can pick a sensible default. Do not leave the array empty just because the user did not articulate the annotation surface; the user reviews and adjusts the proposal in the chat preview.
    - Each entry is discriminated by `kind`. Pick the kind from what `evaluate()` returns:
      - `classification` — `evaluate` returns a bool, an enum-like label, or a `{label, score}` pair. Provide `values` as a list of `{label, score?}`. Use `MAXIMIZE`/`MINIMIZE` when scores are ordered (e.g. `[{label:"good", score:1}, {label:"bad", score:0}]` with `MAXIMIZE`), `NONE` when labels are unordered.
      - `continuous` — `evaluate` returns an open-ended numeric score. Provide `lowerBound`/`upperBound` when the range is known (omit otherwise). Pick `MAXIMIZE` when higher is better, `MINIMIZE` when lower is better.
      - `freeform` — `evaluate` returns a bounded numeric score with a meaningful cutoff (e.g. `0.0`–`1.0` quality scores). Provide `threshold` (the good/bad cutoff combined with the direction), and `lowerBound`/`upperBound` to describe the range. Default to `MAXIMIZE` with `threshold: 0.5`, `lowerBound: 0`, `upperBound: 1` for `[0, 1]` quality scores unless the source suggests otherwise.
    - `optimizationDirection` is REQUIRED on every entry. `MAXIMIZE` = higher is better, `MINIMIZE` = lower is better, `NONE` = unranked. `threshold` has no effect when direction is `NONE`.
    - Supply the evaluator's non-empty `name` on each entry. Do not leave it blank, and do not invent a separate annotation name unless `evaluate()` clearly returns multiple independent signals.
    - Most evaluators have exactly one output config. Only emit multiple entries when `evaluate()` clearly returns several independent signals.
  </output_configs>
  <error_handling>
    - The server validates the `evaluate()` signature and the `name` identifier before persisting and raises `BadRequest` on failure. Surface the server's error message to the user verbatim — do not rephrase or guess at the cause.
    - On a `BadRequest`, no evaluator is created. Fix the source or name and retry; do not call the tool again with the same invalid input.
  </error_handling>
  <guidelines>
    - Prefer real agentic use-cases (e.g. checking JSON validity of a tool-call argument, asserting that an answer cites a retrieved document) over textbook examples.
    - Keep the evaluator focused on one signal. If the user describes several scoring concerns, ask whether they want one evaluator per signal.
    - After the user saves the slideover, briefly summarize what the evaluator scores and confirm that it is attached to the current dataset.
  </guidelines>
</tool>
